{"Title": "Discotic liquid crystals of cucurbit[7]uril (CB[7])-functionalised Laponite clays", "Year": 2018, "Source": "Mol. Phys.", "Volume": "116", "Issue": null, "Art.No": null, "PageStart": 2883, "PageEnd": 2891, "CitedBy": 2, "DOI": "10.1080/00268976.2018.1508778", "Link": "https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&scp=85051830783&origin=inward", "Abstract": "\u00a9 2018, \u00a9 2018 Informa UK Limited, trading as Taylor & Francis Group.Here we demonstrate that in the presence of the small, barrel-shaped molecule cucurbit[7]uril (CB[7]) Laponite clay particles undergo a phase transition into a birefringent gel with lamellar structure and a fluid, Laponite-poor aqueous solution. We employ various characterisation methods and polarised light microscopy to study this transition and the system's structural and optical properties. Furthermore, when dried completely we obtain a layered, transparent composite film, still retaining some liquid-crystalline structure that can be rehydrated reversibly. We argue that this new system may be a model system for anisotropic patchy particles.", "AuthorKeywords": ["Clays", "colloidal gel", "cucurbit[n]uril", "liquid crystals"], "IndexKeywords": ["Colloidal gels", "Cucurbit[n]uril", "Discotic liquid crystal", "Liquid crystalline", "Molecule cucurbit", "Patchy particles", "Structural and optical properties", "Transparent composites"], "DocumentType": "Journal", "PublicationStage": null, "OpenAccess": 0, "EID": "2-s2.0-85051830783", "SubjectAreas": [["Biophysics", "BIOC", "1304"], ["Molecular Biology", "BIOC", "1312"], ["Condensed Matter Physics", "PHYS", "3104"], ["Physical and Theoretical Chemistry", "CHEM", "1606"]], "AuthorData": {"57205055700": {"Name": "Xu P.", "AuthorID": "57205055700", "AffiliationID": "60121115, 60031101", "AffiliationName": "Cavendish Laboratory, University of Cambridge"}, "55329748300": {"Name": "Lan Y.", "AuthorID": "55329748300", "AffiliationID": "60031101", "AffiliationName": "Chemis